    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras are positioned for a high-ceiling offensive output today, anchored by the top-tier efficiency of **Trea Turner** (72.23) and **Yordan Alvarez** (68.04). **Trea Turner** remains an absolute must-start against Pfaadt, where his aggressive base-running profile benefits significantly from a slow delivery transition, providing the elite stolen base floor we prioritize. Similarly, **Yordan Alvarez** overcomes a suboptimal park factor through sheer raw power and a favorable platoon matchup, maintaining his status as our offensive engine. **Colt Keith** (63.90) and **Kyle Schwarber** (65.95) round out our high-efficiency core; **Colt Keith** specifically benefits from an ideal hitting environment and a favorable matchup against Junk, maximizing his scoring potential in the three-hole.\n\nStrategic adjustments were required to navigate some challenging SP xERA matchups. We are starting **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (60.93) despite his risk profile, as his elite sprint speed and favorable platoon advantage against Ashcraft outweigh the negative impact of facing a high-caliber catcher. Conversely, **Christian Yelich** (40.19) and **Josh Smith** (40.06) barely clung to their spots in the lineup; **Christian Yelich** is essentially serving as a placeholder, as the extreme difficulty of facing Griffin (1.76 xERA) nearly pushed him into the bench category. The most difficult personnel decision involved **Carson Benge** (39.27), who fell just shy of our strict 40.0 roster floor. While his base projection was solid, the negative park adjustments and a disadvantageous L/L platoon matchup forced us to keep **Carson Benge** on the bench to preserve our game caps. Likewise, despite his speed profile, **Victor Scott II** (35.35) remains benched due to a poor matchup against Suarez, proving that in our pursuit of stolen bases, efficiency still trumps raw opportunity when the opposing pitcher limits the running game.",
